Virtualization

Virtualization is a technology that enables a single physical computer (server) to operate multiple virtual machines (VMs) through a software layer known as a hypervisor. Each virtual machine functions as an independent system with its own operating system, processor, memory, and storage resources.

By using virtualization, organizations can improve hardware utilization, maintain system isolation, and run different operating systems on the same physical machine.

Example:
A single server can simultaneously run different virtual machines such as a Windows VM, Linux VM, and Ubuntu VM.

Virtualization (House Analogy)

Consider a large house that represents a physical server. The owner divides this house into multiple separate apartments by building walls. Each apartment contains its own facilities such as a kitchen, bedroom, and bathroom, allowing different families to live independently.

Similarly, virtualization splits one physical computer into several virtual machines (VMs). Each VM operates like a separate computer with its own operating system and allocated resources, even though all VMs share the same underlying hardware.

The hypervisor works like the house manager. It supervises and distributes system resources such as CPU, memory, and storage among the different virtual machines.

Mapping of the analogy:

House → Physical Server

Apartments → Virtual Machines (VMs)

House Manager → Hypervisor

Containerization

Containerization is a lightweight approach used to run applications in isolated environments known as containers. Unlike virtualization, containers do not require a full operating system for each application. Instead, they share the host system’s operating system kernel while still maintaining separation between applications and their dependencies.

Because of this architecture, containers are generally faster, more portable, and more resource-efficient than traditional virtual machines.

Example:
Using Docker containers to run multiple applications on a single system without needing separate operating systems for each application.